10.body: Hello World: compact source vs standard Java structure We're only using compact source in lecture Requires --enable-preview in Java 24 Allowed by default in Java 25 Explain parts of program: main(): function, entry point void: keyword, return type {}: code block IO: namespacing println(): function "Hello World": strings

12.body:
void main() { // var input creates a new variable named "input" // IO.readln(...) prints a message and returns whatever the user types // the = stores the result of readln in the input variable var input = IO.readln("Type something: "); IO.print("You typed: "); // printing the variable retrieves whatever was stored in it and prints that // this will repeat whatever the user typed earlier IO.println(input);
} Input and Output (I/O) On terminal (standard in, standard out) Standard out example: ls Standard in (and out) example: jshell Java I/O functions: IO.readln(prompt) IO.println(message) IO.print(message) Store input in variables Write a program that repeats user input
12.title: I/O

13.body: Challenging to think about programs: What goes in your code? What does the computer do for you? What information does the user provide? Common mistake: writing user input in your code Three roles to consider: Programmers write instructions Computers follow instructions Users break things provide input To write good instructions, you need to think about how the computer will follow them and how the user will interact with your program. However, none of that actually goes in your code!
13.breadcrumbs: Week 2 » The Program, Computer, and User » The Program, Computer, and User
13.title: The Program, Computer, and User

14.body: Computers are complicated. How do we understand what they're doing? What can we do that's similar to the following: IO.println IO.readln var x = ... x = ... Easier to understand programs if you can imagine how you would execute their instructions.

15.body: Write a hello world program from scratch. Don't look at any code, but feel free to check your notes if you forgot how to do something. Experiement with the Greeting.java program and find an answer to each of the questions in the comments. Update the Home.java program so that it works for everyone in this classroom. You're only allowed nine lines of code inside the main function: the eight prints/printlns and one variable. Hint: you need to read user input when you create the variable. Finish the Email.java program. It should be able to print your QU email in the "firstname.lastname@quinnipiac.edu" format.
15.title: Practice Exercises

16.body: Questions about week 2 practice? Discuss answers with other people. Get a second and third opinion! LLMs are not reliable and will confidently assert incorrect information. Prove you're right by trying to prove you were wrong. Finding ten examples where your program is right means nothing. One example where your program is wrong means it's wrong. Ask professor (office hours) or tutor (Learning Commons). Goals: after this week you should understand how to explain the difference between statements and expressions explain the difference between literal values, variables, and more complex expressions explain the difference between declaring, initializing, and reassigning a variable declare variables with explicit types convert user input (or other strings) to an int or double write expressions using arithmetic operations on ints and doubles write expressions using string concatenation write expressions using several Math and String functions

24.body: two steps: compile source code into bytecode, then run bytecode on JVM compile error code doesn't run stops compilation early (may hide other compile errors) often syntax-related (syntax errors) better than runtime errors runtime error happens while code is running (already compiled successfully) names ending with "Exception" (e.g. NumberFormatException) crashes the program logic error happens at runtime program works incorrectly but doesn't crash hardest to fix (no crash/error message to tell you about the error)
24.title: Errors

25.body: Stuff from class will be in a public git repository Can download a zip from GitHub in web browser ( https://github.com/zachkohlberg/csc110_25fa_class_repo ) Easier: clone/pull on terminal using git Git installation Linux: use package manager Mac: https://git-scm.com/downloads/mac (try installing Xcode first?) Windows: already got it when you installed Git Bash If you don't have the repo yet, then you can clone it with the following command. Run this command from inside your csc110 folder! git clone https://github.com/zachkohlberg/csc110_25fa_class_repo.git If you already have the repo, then you can update it with the following command. Run this command from inside the cloned repo! git pull Avoid storing your own files in the repo or editing the files in the repo. If you modify anything in the repo, then you may run into errors when you try to update it with the pull command. I'm not going to troubleshoot this with you, so if you mess with the repo and can't pull then you can just make a new clone.

26.body:
Experiment with the Arithmetic.java program and answer the questions in the comments. For each expression below, predict the type (int, double, or String) and value of the expression. After you wrote down your predictions, try entering each expression into jshell to see if you were correct. Try to explain any unexpected results. Note: jshell won't show the type by default, but it will print quotes around a String and a ".0" after a double (even if the double is a whole number). 2 + 2 + 2
"2" + 2 + 2
"2" + (2 + 2)
2 + 2 * 3
(2 + 2) * 3
20 / 7
20 / 7.0
20 % 7
"hello" + "world".toUpperCase()
("hello" + "world").toUpperCase()
Math.max(20, 15.0) Try writing a program that generates a shorter school email address: fmlast@quinnipiac.edu (first initial, middle initial, last name) instead of first.last@quinnipiac.edu. Ask for the user's first name, middle initial, last name, and school name. Use toLowerCase to ensure nothing is capitalized, and use substring to get the user's first initial. Try writing a program that calculates the total minutes from a number of days, hours, and minutes. For example, if a user inputs 4 days, 17 hours, and 11 minutes, then the program should respond with "6791 total minutes." Try writing a program that does the opposite of the previous program: take a number of minutes and convert it to days, hours, and minutes. For example, if a user inputs 6791 minutes, then the program should respond with "4 days, 17 hours, and 11 minutes." This process is similar to the Height.java program.
